Nothing will ever taste as good or as bittersweet as that last slice of Lenny’s Pizza. Growing up in Bensonhurst, this was THE pizzeria but for those not from the neighborhood, you may recognize this was the iconic establishment featured in Saturday Night Fever. You can’t miss the references from the film as John Travolta is all over the walls. He was served a double decker by his real life sister in the film. He also visited in 2018 wearing his legendary white suit. I will always remember this as the place my grandmother and I went to every weekend since I was a baby. Walking up and down 86th was never complete without a slice. I went on dates here. Hung out with friends here. This was a huge part of my life and it will be greatly missed. 💜 #lennyspizza #lennyspizza86 #saturdaynightfever #johntravolta #bensonhurst #brooklynfood #brooklynfoodie #nycfood

Fresh like Neapolitan ice cream 🍨
I’m an apple shape with a little bit of an hourglass - so whenever I wear anything long, draped, or basically anything without structure I become the mayor of  moomoo city. While this may work for some and some may want to cover up, that’s not for me. We are here to show up and show out. Always. 👏🏼 For this look, and many that I wear, I simply added a belt for structure. No one would know why I’m doing it, and it would actually look like a deliberate style choice rather than something done to feel a little better about my body shape. I don’t believe in rules and dressing for your size or shape but we can do things that look a little more flattering (to us!) when we make these choices. Ultimately, it’s a personal choice what you want to wear or don’t, always do what makes you feel comfortable. #appleshape

Native experiences in New York are few and far between, but here are some you can check out on your next visit! 
@relativeartsnyc - They sell native fashions, jewelry, and other goods. It’s a great way to support native designers and crafters. Also, they had a red dress display featuring designers like @lesley_hampton @korinaemmerich @tayloruchytil @himikalas and @jasonbaerg  On May 5th, natives across North America wore red, myself included, to bring awareness and attention to the #mmiw (missing murdered indigenous women) crisis. We wear red to symbolize those who have gone missing, been murdered, been violently or sexually assaulted. We wear a red hand  print on our mouth to symbolize how we are silenced and how the media is silent on our issues. 

@smithsoniannmai Is the Museum of The American Indian and they not only have displays of natives both past and PRESENT- because we are still here 👏🏼 but they also recently had a film festival. They showed To Brooklyn and Back by @reaghant and her family’s history with the back and forth journey. Brooklyn once had its own native community similar to how there are neighborhoods like little Italy and China town, Little Kahnawake was a 10 block stretch in Brookly during the early 1900’s. It’s a great documentary and it reminds us all that not only is this native land but we are the ones who built the modern skylines. 

Have you been to either of these places? 
#relativeartsnyc #nmai #nativeamerican #mmiwg #mmiwawareness #nomorestolensisters #reddressday #notinvisible
